04391nmm a2200733Ia 9780520923027DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20232010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209230277 a10.1525/97805209230272doi  a(DE-B1597)570264  a(OCoLC)1202624400  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aNA1086.M8 7aARC0050002bisacsh04a720/.94336409045223/eng/202311221 aRosenfeld, Gavriel D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMunich and Memory :bArchitecture, Monuments, and the Legacy of the Third Reich /cGavriel D. Rosenfeld.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (456 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWeimar and Now: German Cultural Criticism ;v220 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMunich, notorious in recent history as the capital of the Nazi movement, is the site of Gavriel Rosenfeld's stimulating inquiry into the German collective memory of the Third Reich. Rosenfeld shows, with the aid of a wealth of photographs, how the city's urban form developed after 1945 in direct reflection of its inhabitants' evolving memory of the Second World War and the Nazi dictatorship.In the second half of the twentieth century, the German people's struggle to come to terms with the legacy of Nazism has dramatically shaped nearly all dimensions of their political, social, and cultural life. The area of urban development and the built environment, little explored until now, offers visible evidence of the struggle. By examining the ways in which the people of Munich reconstructed the ruins of their historic buildings, created new works of architecture, dealt with surviving Nazi buildings, and erected new monuments to commemorate the horrors of the recent past, Rosenfeld identifies a spectrum of competing memories of the Nazi experience.Munich’s postwar development was the subject of constant controversy, pitting representatives of contending aesthetic and mnemonic positions against one another in the heated battle to shape the city’s urban form. Examining the debates between traditionalists, modernists, postmodernists, and critical preservationists, Rosenfeld shows that the memory of Nazism in Munich has never been "repressed" but has rather been defined by constant dissension and evolution. On balance, however, he concludes that Munich came to embody in its urban form a conservative view of the past that was inclined to diminish local responsibility for the Third Reich.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitecturexConservation and restorationzGermanyzMunich. 0aArchitecturezGermanyzMunichxHistory. 0aCollective memory and city planningzGermanyzMunich. 0aNational socialism and architecturezGermanyzMunich. 0aReconstruction (1939-1951)zGermanyzMunich. 4a20th century. 4aEuropean history. 4aarchitecture. 4adictatorship. 4afilm. 4ahistory of architecture. 4ahistory of art. 4ahistory of the Americas. 4ahistory. 4aphilosophy. 4apolitical philosophy. 4apreservation. 4asocial philosophy. 4athe arts. 4awar. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520923027?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520923027423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520923027/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles